
[1]derivation

   DERIVATION, n.

   1. The act of deriving, drawing or receiving from a source; as the
   derivation of an estate from ancestors, or of profits from capital, or
   of truth or facts from antiquity.

   2. In grammar, the drawing or tracing of a word from its root or
   original; as, derivation is from the L. Derivo, and the latter from
   rivus, a stream.

   3. A drawing from, or turning aside from, a natural course or channel;
   as the derivation of water from its channel by lateral drains.

   4. A drawing of humors from one part of the body to another; as the
   derivation of humors from the eye, by a blister on the neck.

   5. The thing derived or deduced.
